,"1290–1350":"1290–1350","1300–Female":"1300–Overleden","1324":"1324","20 Nov 1378":"20 november 1378","1323":"1323","1378":"1378","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1394":"1394","1406":"1406","1290":"1290","Bradenlove, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1324–1406":"1324–1406","1320–1378":"1320–1378","1355–1394":"1355–1394","1290–1350":"1290–1350","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1324":"1324","20 Nov 1378":"20 November 1378","1323":"1323","1378":"1378","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1394":"1394","1406":"1406","1290":"1290","Bradenlove, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Wymondham, Norfolk, England":"Wymondham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Staundon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin, Ciaran, Cormac.","English and Irish: variant of   Stanton  . This English name has been established (in this spelling) since medieval times in Ireland (Mayo, Connacht), where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Stonndún</b>. Compare   McEvilly  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McEvilly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamonn.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Mhílidh</b> ‘son of the knight’, from Gaelic <i>míleadh</i> ‘warrior, knight’. In County Mayo and County Cork, a family of English origin Gaelicized their name from   Staunton   to <i>Mac an Mhílidh</i>, apparently because of the latter's presumed similarity to the name of their ancestor, <i>Milo</i> de Stanton."]},{"name":"Stanton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in England called Stanton or Staunton, especially Stanton in Staffordshire and Staunton in Worcestershire, all named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Most of the placenames come from their situation on stony ground, but in the case of Stanton Harcourt in Oxfordshire and Stanton Drew in Avon the reference is to the proximity of prehistoric stone monuments. The name has also sometimes been chosen by Ashkenazic Jews as an Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames. This surname has also long been established in Ireland (especially Mayo)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Staundon was born in 1324, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard de Staundon, was 35 and her mother, Mrs Richard De Staundon, was 25. She had at least 1 daughter with Adam de Wymondham. She died in 1406, in Wym